key "Shen2016"

\end_inset

, and widely used diploid GWAS software, as Plink 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Purcell2007"

\end_inset

 and Tassel 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bradbury2007"

\end_inset

, have been also used to analyze polyploids organisms by 
\begin_inset Quotes fld
\end_inset

diploidizing
\begin_inset Quotes frd
\end_inset

 the marker data 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lindqvist2014,Shulz2016"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, each tool has its own way of doing things: different user interfaces
 (GUI or command line based), different input formats (phenotype and genotype
 formats), different models and algorithm assumptions, and different outputs.
 Consequently, in light of all these considerations, researchers must spend
 great effort when they try to replicate GWAS results by using different
 tools.
 With this in mind, we developed the MultiGWAS tool that with a single input
 it performs GWAS analyses by using four different GWAS software in such
 a way to help researchers in the selection of true associations across
 GWAS.
 The tool scans the different results files, calculates new scores and threshold
s from resulting markers, select best ranked and significative makers, and
 create summary tables and plots that show in an intuitive manner the common
 and different markers found by the four tools.
\end_layout

