\begin_layout Subsection
Multi analysis phase
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two types of GWAS analyses can be conducted by MultiGWAS: Full and Naive.
 The first with control for population structure and individual relatedness;
 and the second without any of these controls.
 Controlling of population structure is based on the principal components
 (PCs).
 Each software calculates the PCs and uses the top ten as covariates in
 the association analysis, while controlling of individual relatedness is
 based on kinship matrices calculated by each software, in the case of Tassel
 and GWASpoly, and calculated externally by the king software 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Manichaikul2010"

\end_inset

, in the case of Plink and SHEsis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The allowed format for the marker data is the 
\begin_inset Quotes sld
\end_inset

ACGT
\begin_inset Quotes srd
\end_inset

 configuration which is suitable for the polyploid tools GWASpoly and SHEsis,
 but not for the diploid tools Plink and Tassel.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
which need a diploid genotype (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Quotes sld
\end_inset

AT
\begin_inset Quotes srd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes sld
\end_inset

CG
\begin_inset Quotes srd
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

So, our MultiGWAS tool 
\begin_inset Quotes sld
\end_inset

diploidizes
\begin_inset Quotes srd
\end_inset

 the tetraploid marker data for these two tools by coding each marker in
 two ways: all possible homozygous genotypes (AAAA, CCCC, GGGG, TTTT), are
 coded with two nucleotides (AA, CC, GG, and TT); and all possible heterozygous
 genotypes (e.g.
 AAAT, ...
 ,CCCG) are coded with the combination of their reference and alternate
 alleles calculated from the tetraploid marker (e.g.
 AT, ...
 ,CG).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the filtered genotype and phenotype are ready for the four tools, each
 tool is executed in parallel by MultiGWAS using a parameterized script
 for each tool.
 Each script is called using as arguments the filtered genotype and phenotype
 along with the set of specified values for the arguments described in section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
